<div class="experiment-section">
  <h4><i class="fas fa-bullseye me-2"></i>üéØ Learning Objectives:</h4>
  <ul class="objectives-list">
    <li>Verify Archimedes' principle that an object immersed in a fluid experiences an upward buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid displaced.</li>
    <li>Determine the relationship between an object's density and whether it sinks or floats.</li>
    <li>Measure the buoyant force acting on objects of different masses and volumes.</li>
    <li>Calculate the volume of an irregularly shaped object using the principle of water displacement.</li>
    <li>Understand and apply the formula: <code>F<sub>buoyant</sub> = œÅ<sub>fluid</sub> √ó g √ó V<sub>object</sub></code>.</li>
    <li>Observe how the apparent weight of an object changes when submerged in a fluid.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="experiment-section">
  <h4><i class="fas fa-tools me-2"></i>üõ†Ô∏è How to Perform the Experiment:</h4>
  <div class="procedure-steps">
    <div class="procedure-step">
      <h5>1. Prepare the Equipment:</h5>
      <p>Set up a spring balance, a beaker filled with water (or another liquid), and objects of different masses and densities.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="procedure-step">
      <h5>2. Measure in Air:</h5>
      <p>Measure the weight of each object in air using the spring balance and record this as the true weight.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="procedure-step">
      <h5>3. Measure in Liquid:</h5>
      <p>Completely submerge each object in the liquid while still attached to the spring balance. Record this as the apparent weight.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="procedure-step">
      <h5>4. Calculate Buoyant Force:</h5>
      <p>Calculate the buoyant force by finding the difference between the true weight and the apparent weight (F<sub>buoyant</sub> = W<sub>air</sub> - W<sub>liquid</sub>).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="procedure-step">
      <h5>5. Measure Displaced Liquid:</h5>
      <p>For regularly shaped objects, calculate their volume mathematically. For irregular objects, use water displacement to measure their volume.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="procedure-step">
      <h5>6. Verify the Principle:</h5>
      <p>Calculate the expected buoyant force using Archimedes' principle (F<sub>buoyant</sub> = œÅ<sub>liquid</sub> √ó g √ó V<sub>object</sub>) and compare with your measured value.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="procedure-step">
      <h5>7. Vary Parameters:</h5>
      <p>Change the density of the liquid or use objects of different densities to observe how this affects the buoyant force and whether objects sink or float.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="experiment-section">
  <h4><i class="fas fa-check-circle me-2"></i>‚úÖ What You Will Learn:</h4>
  <ul class="outcomes-list">
    <li>An object experiences an upward buoyant force equal to the weight of the fluid it displaces.</li>
    <li>Objects with density less than the fluid will float; those with greater density will sink.</li>
    <li>The buoyant force depends on the density of the fluid, not the density of the object.</li>
    <li>How to calculate the volume of an irregularly shaped object using water displacement.</li>
    <li>The relationship between an object's weight in air, its apparent weight in liquid, and the buoyant force.</li>
    <li>How to apply Archimedes' principle to solve practical problems in fluid mechanics.</li>
  </ul>
</div>
